  <h1>Federated Synthetic Data Analysis Using synthpop</h1>

  <div class="meta">
    Master’s Thesis Project | Biostatistics | Simulation Study | Privacy-Preserving Methods
  </div>

  <hr>

  <div class="section">
    <h2>1. Abstract</h2>
    <p>
      This project investigates the utility of synthetic longitudinal data generated using the
      <i>synthpop</i> framework, with a focus on privacy-preserving statistical analysis in
      multi-site biomedical studies. The study evaluates whether synthetic data can reproduce
      inferential validity comparable to original data in mixed-effects modeling settings.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <h2>2. Objective</h2>
    <div class="box">
      To evaluate the statistical validity, utility, and variability of synthetic longitudinal data
      generated under a federated-like framework, compared to original clinical data.
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <h2>3. Methods</h2>

    <h3>3.1 Data Generation</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Synthetic data generated using <b>synthpop</b></li>
      <li>Multi-site longitudinal structure</li>
      <li>Random intercept mixed-effects framework</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>3.2 Simulation Design</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Repeated simulation studies (Monte Carlo framework)</li>
      <li>Comparison of synthetic vs original datasets</li>
      <li>Fixed and random effects evaluated</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>3.3 Models</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Linear mixed-effects models</li>
      <li>Random intercept models across sites</li>
      <li>Parameter estimation under repeated sampling</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <h2>4. Performance Measures</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Bias</li>
      <li>Variance</li>
      <li>Mean Squared Error (MSE)</li>
      <li>Coverage Probability</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <h2>5. Key Contributions</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Evaluation of synthetic data utility in longitudinal settings</li>
      <li>Assessment of privacy-preserving modeling approaches</li>
      <li>Comparison of synthetic vs original inference stability</li>
    </ul>
